import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from PIL import Image

# Directories for each dataset
train_dir = './data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/train'
val_dir = './data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/validation'
test_dir = './data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/test'

# Check the distribution of classes in the three datasets
train_cats = len(os.listdir(f"{train_dir}/cat"))
train_dogs = len(os.listdir(f"{train_dir}/dog"))

val_cats = len(os.listdir(f"{val_dir}/cat"))
val_dogs = len(os.listdir(f"{val_dir}/dog"))

test_cats = len(os.listdir(f"{test_dir}/cat"))
test_dogs = len(os.listdir(f"{test_dir}/dog"))

print(f"Train - Cats: {train_cats}, Dogs: {train_dogs}")
print(f"Validation - Cats: {val_cats}, Dogs: {val_dogs}")
print(f"Test - Cats: {test_cats}, Dogs: {test_dogs}")

# Visualize some images from each dataset
def plot_images(path, n=5):
    files = os.listdir(path)[:n]  # Take the first n files
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, n, figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, file in enumerate(files):
        img = Image.open(os.path.join(path, file))
        axs[i].imshow(img)
        axs[i].axis("off")
    plt.show()

# Show some images of cats and dogs from each dataset
print("Sample Cat Images from Training Set")
plot_images(f"{train_dir}/cat")

print("Sample Dog Images from Training Set")
plot_images(f"{train_dir}/dog")

print("Sample Cat Images from Validation Set")
plot_images(f"{val_dir}/cat")

print("Sample Dog Images from Validation Set")
plot_images(f"{val_dir}/dog")

print("Sample Cat Images from Test Set")
plot_images(f"{test_dir}/cat")

print("Sample Dog Images from Test Set")
plot_images(f"{test_dir}/dog")

In [95]:
# image statistics
def analyze_image_statistics(dataset):
    pixel_mean = []
    pixel_std = []
    for images, _ in dataset:
        pixel_mean.append(tf.reduce_mean(images))
        pixel_std.append(tf.math.reduce_std(images))
    
    return {
        'mean': tf.reduce_mean(pixel_mean),
        'std': tf.reduce_mean(pixel_std)
    }

stats = analyze_image_statistics(train_dataset)
print("\nImage Statistics:")
print(f"Mean pixel value: {stats['mean']:.2f}")
print(f"Std pixel value: {stats['std']:.2f}")

# class names
class_names = train_dataset.class_names
print("\nClass names:", class_names)

# image counts
def count_images_per_class(dataset):
    counts = {name: 0 for name in class_names}
    for images, labels in dataset:
        for label in labels:
            counts[class_names[label.numpy()]] += 1
    return counts

train_counts = count_images_per_class(train_dataset)
print("\nImages per class in training set:", train_counts)

# show images
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.bar(class_names, list(train_counts.values()))
plt.title('Number of Images per Class Train dataset')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

3 Train two networks¶

3.1 Define a Neural Network - Convnet From Scratch¶

Definning the model¶

In [10]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers

# Define the input
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))

# Rescaling the image pixels (normalization)
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)

# First convolutional layer (32 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

# Second convolutional layer (64 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

# Third convolutional layer (128 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

# Fourth convolutional layer (256 filters, 3x3 kernel, ReLU activation)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

# Flatten layer to convert 2D matrix to a 1D vector
x = layers.Flatten()(x)

# Dropout layer to prevent overfitting (regularization)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)

# Output layer with 1 neuron (binary classification) and sigmoid activation
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

# Create the model
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

# Display the model summary
model.summary()

Model: "functional_3"

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="./models/convnet_from_scratch.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss")
]
history = model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=30,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks)

3.2.2 Fast feature extraction without data augmentation¶

Extracting the VGG16 features and corresponding labels

Note: running the following cell on a CPU will take about 10 minutes

In [18]:
import numpy as np

def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(images)
        features = conv_base.predict(preprocessed_images)
        all_features.append(features)
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features, train_labels =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset)
val_features, val_labels =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset)
test_features, test_labels =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset)

In [23]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
acc = history.history["accuracy"]
val_acc = history.history["val_accuracy"]
loss = history.history["loss"]
val_loss = history.history["val_loss"]
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, "b", label="Validation accuracy")
plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.figure()
plt.plot(epochs, loss, "bo", label="Training loss")
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, "b", label="Validation loss")
plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.figure()
plt.plot(epochs, loss, "bo", label="Training loss")
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, "b", label="Validation loss")
plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

4.2 Confusion matrix , classification_report, precision_recall_curve¶

In [85]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, classification_report, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load the best models
from tensorflow.keras.models import load_model

convnet_model = load_model("./models/convnet_from_scratch.keras")
feature_extraction_model = load_model("./models/feature_extraction.keras")
feature_extraction_aug_model = load_model("./models/feature_extraction_with_data_augmentation.keras")
fine_tuned_model = load_model("./models/fine_tuning.keras")

# Predictions and evaluation
def evaluate_model(model, dataset, true_labels, dataset_type="test_dataset"):
    print(f"\nEvaluating model on {dataset_type}:")
    # Get predictions (probabilities)
    if dataset_type == "test_dataset":
        probs = model.predict(dataset).ravel()
    else:  # test_features and test_labels
        probs = model.predict(dataset).ravel()
    preds = np.round(probs)  # Convert to binary labels
    
    # Classification metrics
    print("Confusion Matrix:")
    print(confusion_matrix(true_labels, preds))
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print(classification_report(true_labels, preds))
    
    # Precision-Recall curve
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(true_labels, probs)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f"{dataset_type} - Precision-Recall")
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.title(f"Precision-Recall Curve - {dataset_type}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Evaluate each model

# ConvNet from Scratch
evaluate_model(convnet_model, test_dataset, test_labels, "ConvNet")

# Feature Extraction
evaluate_model(feature_extraction_model, test_features, test_labels, "Feature Extraction")

# Feature Extraction with Data Augmentation
evaluate_model(feature_extraction_aug_model, test_dataset, test_labels, "Feature Extraction with Augmentation")

# Fine-Tuning
evaluate_model(fine_tuned_model, test_dataset, test_labels, "Fine-Tuned Model")

Conclusions¶

  • Based on the accuracy value of 0.9791 , it could be said that the feature extraction with data augmentation model is the best, but if we look at its training and validation graph we see that it has overfitting , however the Fine Tuning model has a value of 0.9741 and its training and validation graph no longer has overfitting. According to this metric, Fini Tunning would be the best.
  • Based on the confusion matrix , precision recall and f1 score it could be said that all models show a fairly similar performance with precision and F1-score close to 0.50, suggesting that none of the models is learning well to classify between the two classes.
  • Considering the small increase in precision and F1-score, the "Feature Extraction" and "Feature Extraction with Data Augmentation" models seem slightly superior, but in general, the performance is very low in all models.
  • Fine tuning in this iteration has not helped to improve, possibly we could change the number of layers to defrost and not take in this case it was [-6] it is suggested to test with [-7] to continue evaluating the performance of the model and also change the number of epochs in this case 30 was used it could be tested with 40 and analyze how the model is improving.
